The [[English language|English]] word ''love'' can have a variety of related but distinct meanings in different contexts. Often, other languages use multiple words to express some of the different concepts which English relies mainly on ''love'' to encapsulate; one example is the plurality of [[Greek words for love|Greek words for "love"]]. Cultural differences in conceptualizing love thus make it doubly difficult to establish any universal definition.<ref>Kay, Paul. "What Is the Sapir-Whorf Hypothesis?". ''American Anthropologist'', New Series, Volume 86, No. 1, March, 1984. pp. 65-79</ref>
